{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017mEQSnXhikWxpZ6KxciA3v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"rabbitmq-2 is running as a standalone single-node cluster with its own cluster ID. The root cause is confirmed: the wrong Erlang cookie (`driftedcookie` vs `supersecretcookie`).\n\nThe fix:\n1. Fix the `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` secret to give `rabbitmq-2` the correct cookie (`supersecretcookie`)\n2. Stop the RabbitMQ application on rabbitmq-2 and reset its Mnesia state while still running, OR\n3. Delete the pod (it will restart with the corrected secret → init container copies the correct cookie)\n4. The tricky part is that rabbitmq-2 has stale Mnesia data from running as its own solo cluster. The safest approach is to fix the secret first, then exec into the pod and run `rabbitmqctl reset` to clear the Mnesia state before deleting it, so it rejoins the cluster fresh with the correct cookie. Reconsidering whether we actually need to call `rabbitmqctl reset` before deleting the pod—the peer discovery plugin's startup behavior depends on whether it detects existing cluster data or a fresh node. If rabbitmq-2 still has its old Mnesia data when it restarts with the correct cookie, it might try to stay as a single-node cluster rather than joining the existing one, so resetting first is the safer approach to ensure a clean join. Patching the secret to update rabbitmq-2's cookie, then stopping the app and resetting its Mnesia database to clear the conflicting cluster state, deleting the pod so it restarts fresh and rejoins the existing cluster through peer discovery.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4805,"cache_read_input_tokens":35956,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4805},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5f2470b6-5c6e-4087-89ee-e362fe206b09","uuid":"a3b58932-97c4-44f3-af9a-c3081c85ac83","request_id":"req_011CcMQLsLeWX1C7TXTUCqiB"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017mEQSnXhikWxpZ6KxciA3v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Root cause confirmed:** `rabbitmq-2` is running with cookie `driftedcookie` while `rabbitmq-0` and `rabbitmq-1` use `supersecretcookie`. The cookie mismatch prevents Erlang clustering. Additionally, rabbitmq-2 formed its own standalone cluster with a different cluster ID — so we must reset its Mnesia state before rejoining.\n\n**Fix plan:**\n1. Patch the secret to give `rabbitmq-2` the correct cookie\n2. Reset rabbitmq-2's Mnesia state (clears stale solo-cluster data)\n3. Delete the pod → restart with correct cookie → peer discovery rejoins the cluster\n\n**Step 1:** Fix the secret."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4805,"cache_read_input_tokens":35956,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4805},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5f2470b6-5c6e-4087-89ee-e362fe206b09","uuid":"9224837b-d59a-4a7e-86b1-b38fbbba42e7","request_id":"req_011CcMQLsLeWX1C7TXTUCqiB"}
