{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Jrxctr2VN9QAEEkzr7PepZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The cluster is fully restored. Here's a summary of what was done and why:\n\n**Root cause:** The `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` Secret had a different Erlang cookie for `rabbitmq-2` (`driftedcookie`) than for `rabbitmq-0`/`rabbitmq-1` (`supersecretcookie`). Erlang nodes refuse to cluster with peers that have a different cookie, so rabbitmq-2 started as an isolated single-node cluster.\n\n**Fix (3 steps, all using native Kubernetes resources):**\n\n1. **Patched the Secret** — corrected `rabbitmq-2`'s entry in `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` to `supersecretcookie` (same base64 value as the other two nodes).\n\n2. **Reset Mnesia state** on the running rabbitmq-2 pod (`rabbitmqctl stop_app` + `rabbitmqctl reset`) — necessary because rabbitmq-2 had already formed its own standalone cluster with a different cluster ID; without this reset, restarting with the correct cookie would still cause a Mnesia conflict on join.\n\n3. **Deleted the pod** — the StatefulSet recreated it; the `copy-cookie` init container re-read the now-correct secret and wrote `supersecretcookie` to the emptyDir cookie volume. RabbitMQ started with the matching cookie, Kubernetes peer discovery found rabbitmq-0 and rabbitmq-1, and rabbitmq-2 joined as the third disk node.\n\n**Final state:** All 3 nodes in `Disk Nodes` and `Running Nodes`, no alarms, no network partitions."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2040,"cache_read_input_tokens":43520,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2040},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5f2470b6-5c6e-4087-89ee-e362fe206b09","uuid":"66e5ab33-727b-4790-82b4-87e11efd2105","request_id":"req_011CcMQVDPdRzRB3kSftX2FK"}
